eath’, probably a nickname denoting a habitual wearer of such items, or a metonymic occupational name for a maker of them.","English: perhaps from the Old French personal name <i>Gerland</i> (ancient Germanic <i>Garuland</i>, probably from <i>garw-</i> ‘war-gear; prepared(ness)’ + <i>land</i> ‘land’; the first element of the French name may instead be from a name beginning with <i>gēr</i> ‘spear’).","English: topographic name from Middle English <i>gor(e)</i>, <i>gar(e)</i> ‘triangular piece’ + <i>lond</i> ‘land’ (Old English <i>gāra</i> + <i>land</i>, <i>lond</i>), for someone who lived ‘(at the) triangular piece of land’. Compare   Garfield  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Gerland","meanings":["English (North Yorkshire and Lancashire): variant of   Garland  . This surname is now rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Garfield","meanings":["English (Midlands): topographic name from Middle English <i>gor(e)</i>, <i>gar(e)</i> ‘triangular piece’ + <i>feld</i> ‘open country, field’ (Old English <i>gār</i> + <i>feld</i>), for someone who lived by a triangular piece of land.","English: alternatively, sometimes perhaps a variant of   Carville   (a name of Norman origin), with excrescent final <i>-d</i>.","Americanized form of one or more similar (like-sounding) Jewish surnames."]},{"name":"Gartland","meanings":["Irish and English: variant of   Garland  .","Irish (northern Leinster and southern Ulster): shortened Anglicized form of <b>Mac Gearnúin</b>, a patronymic from the Norman personal name   Gernon  ."]}]},{"name":"Guillaume","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Germanic.  See  <b>William</b> ."],"variants":[{"name":"William","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Guillaume DE GARLANDE V was born about 1160, in Europe, his father, Guillaume de Garlande IV, was 36 and his mother, Idoine DE CHAUMONT, was 32. He married Adèle DE CHÂTILLON-SUR-MARNE in 1193. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died in 1216, at the age of 57."},"et":{"environ 1160–1216":"umbes 1160–1216","1160–1216":"1160–1216","1165–1216":"1165–1216","1200–1259":"1200–1259","1125–1191":"1125–1191","1130–1208":"1130–1208","environ 1200":"umbes 1200","1165":"1165","environ 1160":"umbes 1160","1130":"1130","1193":"1193","1160":"1160","1191":"1191","1216":"1216","1259":"1259","1125":"1125","1200":"1200","environ 1208":"umbes 1208","1208":"1208","Livry-sur-Vesle, Marne, Champagne-Ardenne, France":"Livry-sur-Vesle, Marne, Champagne-Ardenne, Prantsusmaa","Europe":"Europe"},"fi":{"environ 1160–1216":"noin 1160–1216","1160–1216":"1160–1216","1165–1216":"1165–1216","1200–1259":"1200–1259","1125–1191":"1125–1191","1130–1208":"1130–1208","environ 1200":"noin 1200","1165":"1165","environ 1160":"noin 1160","1130":"1130","1193":"1193","1160":"1160","1191":"1191","1216":"1216","1259":"1259","1125":"1125","1200":"1200","environ 1208":"noin 1208","1208":"1208","Livry-sur-Vesle, Marne, Champagne-Ardenne, France":"Livry-sur-Vesle, Marne, Champagne-Ardenne, Ranska","Europe":"Europe"},"fr":{"environ 1160–1216":"environ 1160–1216","1160–1216":"1160–1216","1165–1216":"1165–1216","1200–1259":"1200–1259","1125–1191":"1125–1191","1130–1208":"1130–1208","environ 1200":"environ 1200","1165":"1165","environ 1160":"environ 1160","1130":"1130","1193":"1193","1160":"1160","1191":"1191","1216":"1216","1259":"1259","1